{{Use South African English|date=August 2012}}
'''Makana Football Association''' was a sporting body formed by political prisoners on [[Robben Island]], [[South Africa]] who organised [[association football|football]] leagues for fellow inmates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=554548.html|title=Tokyo Sexwale: Football kept us alive|date=18 July 2007|accessdate=2009-11-03|publisher=[[FIFA]]}}</ref> Formed in 1966, the association ran a league until 1973, adhering strictly to the [[Laws of the Game (association football)|Laws of the Game]],<ref name=Zumaref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southafrica.info/2010/zuma-referee.htm|title=Fifa gives Zuma his ref's certificate|date=30 June 2009|accessdate=2009-11-03|publisher=SouthAfrica.info}}</ref> the FIFA rulebook being one of the few books in the prison library.<ref name=WSC/> It was named after the 19th century [[Xhosa people|Xhosa]] warrior-prophet [[Makana (prophet)|Makana]], who was himself imprisoned on Robben Island.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/06/sports/soccer/06robben.html|title= Origins of Tournament in an Infamous Prison|work=New York Times|date=5 July 2010|accessdate=2012-01-04}}</ref>

Prior to this, the game had been banned by the prison authorities, but starting in December 1964, prisoners took it turns to "...request to be allowed to play football" every Saturday.<ref name=WSC>{{cite web|url=http://www.wsc.co.uk/content/view/2843/28/|title=BOOK REVIEWS:General:More Than Just A Game|publisher=''[[When Saturday Comes]]''|accessdate=2009-11-05|first=Mike|last= Ticher|date=February 2009}}</ref>    At one point the F.A. was running three leagues, with teams from nine clubs competing.<ref name=metro>{{cite web|url=http://www.metro.co.uk/news/newsfocus/article.html?On_the_football_pitch_we_were_free&in_article_id=359884&in_page_id=65|title='On the football pitch we were free'|first=Chris|last=Stocks|date=16 October 2008|accessdate=2009-11-04|publisher= Metro (UK)}}</ref> The organisation crossed the political divides in the prison, between the [[African National Congress|ANC]] and the [[Pan Africanist Congress of Azania|PAC]], with over half of the inmates involved in the leagues.<ref name=metro/> A small group of prisoners, including [[Nelson Mandela]], [[Walter Sisulu]], [[Govan Mbeki]] and [[Ahmed Kathrada]] were, however, barred from participating in or even watching the matches.<ref name=morethan/>

The Makana F.A. was given honorary membership of [[FIFA]] in 2007,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/worldNews/idUSL1884263520070718|title=Prison soccer league in spotlight on Mandela birthday|date=18 July 2007|accessdate=2009-11-03|publisher=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> and in the same year a film was made telling the story of the F.A., entitled ''[[More Than Just a Game]]''.<ref name=morethan>{{cite web|url=http://www.southafrica.info/news/arts/morethanjustagame.htm|title=Football 'more than just a game'|date=26 November 2007|accessdate=2009-11-04|publisher=SouthAfrica.info}}</ref> Former [[President of South Africa]], [[Jacob Zuma]], was a Makana F.A. [[referee (association football)|referee]].<ref name=Zumaref/> Others involved in the F.A.'s organisation included [[Steve Tshwete]], [[Dikgang Moseneke]], and [[Tokyo Sexwale]].<ref name=metro/><ref name=Zumaref/>

