{{use dmy dates|date=January 2013}} {{Infobox military person |name='''Nabil Sahraoui''' |birth_date=26 September 1969 |birth_place= [[Batna, Algeria]] |death_date=20 June 2004 (aged 34) |death_place= |image=Nabil Sahraoui.jpg |caption= |allegiance=[[Al-Qaeda Organization in the Islamic Maghreb]] |serviceyears= |rank=Emir |commands= |unit= |battles=Islamic insurgency in Algeria |awards= |laterwork=}}
'''Nabil Sahraoui''' (26 September 1969 – 20 June 2004), alias '''Mustapha Abou Ibrahim''', was an Algerian [[Islamist]] militant, and the head of the radical ''Groupe Salafiste pour la Prédication et le Combat'' (GSPC, later renamed [[Al-Qaeda Organization in the Islamic Maghreb]]) from August 2003 until his death the following year.
==Early life== Sahraoui was born in [[Batna, Algeria]], on 26 September 1966.<ref name=iwire>{{cite news|title=Algerian Islamist GSPC leader Nabil Sahraoui profiled|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-21485118_ITM|accessdate=23 January 2013|newspaper=Asia Africa Intelligence Wire|date=28 May 2004}}</ref>
==GSPC== In 2003, Sahraoui replaced [[Hassan Hattab]] as the leader of the GSPC, since the latter was removed from the post due to his view that reconciliation with the government should be encouraged.<ref name=tawil>{{cite journal|last=Tawil|first=Camille|title=New Strategies in al-Qaeda’s Battle for Algeria|journal=Terrorism Monitor|date=27 July 2009|volume=7|issue=22|url=https://www.cimicweb.org/cmo/medbasin/Documents/North%20Africa/Security/New%20Strategies-AQ%20battle%20for%20Algeria.pdf|accessdate=21 January 2013}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In October 2003, Sahraoui pledged allegiance as GSPC leader to both [[Usama bin Ladin]]'s [[Al Qaeda]] organization and to the Taliban leader [[Mullah Omar]].<ref name=guido>{{cite journal|last=Steinberg|first=Guido|title=Towards a "political turn" in the fight against Jihadist terrorism|journal=Politique Etrangere|year=2008|pages=175–187|url=http://www.swp-berlin.org/fileadmin/contents/products/fachpublikationen/ksSteinberg_Political_Turn.pdf|accessdate=23 January 2013}}</ref>
==Death== Sahraoui was killed in a shootout with the [[Algerian army]] in the Kabylie region on 20 June 2004 at age 34.<ref name=gsecurity>{{cite web|title=Nabil Sahraoui|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/security/profiles/nabil_sahraoui.htm|publisher=Global Security|accessdate=23 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2004/06/21/2003175948 ''Algerian armed forces say rebel leader is killed'' Taipei Times (Reuters report), 21 June 2004]</ref><ref name=fnews2004>{{cite news|title=Algerian Military Says Terror Leader Killed|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,123181,00.html|accessdate=24 January 2013|newspaper=Fox News|date=20 June 2004|agency=AP}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Staff writer | title = Chronology Of events: 2005 | journal = [[Mediterranean Politics]], special issue: Transnational Islam and Regional Security: Cooperation and Diversity between Europe and North Africa | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 279–308 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/13629390600683048 | date = July 2006 | url = https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/13629390600683048 | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref> His top aides were also killed in the military sweep.<ref name=cpress>{{cite news|title=Algerian military says top guerrilla leader Nabil Sahraoui killed in army sweep|url=http://www.politicsandcurrentaffairs.com/Forum/showthread.php?t=5882|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130216155249/http://www.politicsandcurrentaffairs.com/Forum/showthread.php?t=5882|dead-url=yes|archive-date=16 February 2013|accessdate=24 January 2013|newspaper=Canadian Press|date=20 June 2004}}</ref>
Sahraoui was replaced as head of the GSPC by [[Abu Musab Abdel Wadoud]] over the objections of former leader [[Hassan Hattab]].<ref name=tawil/>
